# Environment & Secrets

Canonical examples: `.env.example` (Docker prod ports) and `.env.development.example` (`pnpm dev` ports). **Never commit** real `.env`.

## Required categories (from `.env.example`)

| Area | Keys |
|---|---|
| URLs / ports | `APP_URL`, `API_URL`, `NEXT_PUBLIC_API_URL`, `API_PORT`, `WEB_PORT` |
| Data | `DATABASE_URL`, `REDIS_URL` |
| Auth | `JWT_ACCESS_SECRET`, `JWT_REFRESH_SECRET` (min length — no silent weak default) |
| Media | `S3_*` |
| Email | `SMTP_*`, `EMAIL_FROM` |
| Payments | `PAYMENT_PROVIDER`, `PAYMENT_KEY_*`, `PAYMENT_WEBHOOK_SECRET` |
| Logs | `LOG_LEVEL` |

## Port split (easy footgun)

| Mode | Web | API |
|---|---|---|
| Docker prod (`deploy-vps`) | **3001** | **4001** |
| Local `pnpm dev` | **3101** | **4101** |

Never point `pnpm dev` at 3001/4001 while `inabiya-web` / `inabiya-api` containers own those ports. See `Docs/PORTS.md`.

## Rules

- `.env.example` = placeholders only (the checked-in `change-me-…` / local stub secrets are fine; production values stay off git).
- Fail fast if critical secrets missing at boot.
- Client may only see explicit `NEXT_PUBLIC_*` (today: API URL) — no JWT/payment secrets in the browser bundle.
- New env key → document in Memory session log + update the matching `.env*.example`.
- Don’t hardcode credentials in Dockerfiles, Caddy site files, or source.
